1.vid: /e/ed/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 1 Version 4.360p.mp4

2.text: Blot the excess cooking oil out with a paper towel.
2.vid: /e/ec/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 2 Version 5.360p.mp4

3.text: Cover the stain with baking soda.
3.vid: /c/ca/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 3 Version 5.360p.mp4

4.text: Let the baking soda sit for 30 to 60 minutes, then scrub it out with an old toothbrush.
4.vid: /9/96/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 4 Version 5.360p.mp4

5.text: Pour some dish soap over the baking soda.
5.vid: /7/70/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 5 Version 5.360p.mp4

6.text: Wash the garment in the washing machine.
6.vid: /c/ce/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 6.360p.mp4

7.text: Make sure that the stain is completely gone before you use the dryer.

9.text: Start by covering the stain with cornstarch and brushing it off after 30 minutes.
9.vid: /c/c9/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 9 Version 2.360p.mp4

10.text: Put the sweater down on the paper and trace it with a pencil or pen.
10.vid: /2/2d/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 10 Version 2.360p.mp4

11.text: Fill a sink with cold water.
11.vid: /2/26/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 11 Version 2.360p.mp4

12.text: Add a few drops of dish soap into the water.
12.vid: /b/b2/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 12 Version 2.360p.mp4

13.text: Put the sweater into the water and gently swish it around.
13.vid: /d/d9/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 13 Version 2.360p.mp4

14.text: Let the sweater sit for two to three minutes before pulling it out.

15.text: Drain the dirty water and fill the sink with fresh water so that you can rinse the sweater.
15.vid: /3/3f/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 15 Version 2.360p.mp4

16.text: Dry the sweater by rolling it up in a large towel.
16.vid: /e/ea/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 16 Version 2.360p.mp4

17.text: Put the sweater back onto the sheet of paper and stretch it until it's back to its original shape.
17.vid: /e/e1/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 17 Version 3.360p.mp4

18.text: Know how to handle other wool fabrics.

20.text: Put a piece of cardboard inside the garment, behind the stain.
20.vid: /9/94/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 20 Version 3.360p.mp4

21.text: Spray the stain with some WD-40.
21.vid: /9/92/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 21 Version 3.360p.mp4

22.text: Use an old toothbrush to scrub some baking soda into the stain.
22.vid: /7/79/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 22 Version 2.360p.mp4

23.text: Repeat the baking soda treatment until you have no more clumps.
23.vid: /2/25/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 23 Version 3.360p.mp4

24.text: Pour some dish soap onto the baking soda.
24.vid: /3/34/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 24 Version 3.360p.mp4

25.text: Wash the garment in the washing machine according to the tag.

26.text: Make sure that the stain is gone before using the dryer.

28.text: Know how to handle dry-clean-only fabrics.

29.text: Treat the stain with cornstarch and dish soap.
29.vid: /6/68/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 29 Version 2.360p.mp4

30.text: Use some hairspray to dissolve the stain.
30.vid: /8/80/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 30 Version 3.360p.mp4

31.text: Try using hydrogen peroxide, baking soda, and dish soap.
31.vid: /f/f0/Get a Cooking Oil Stain out of Clothing Step 31 Version 2.360p.mp4

32.text: Use some aloe vera, dish soap, or shampoo as a pre-wash stain remover.

33.text: Try using a store-bought pre-wash stain remover.
